I am now trying to find a sequence via the PaintingBinding.shaderWarmUp itself that triggers the shaders that are not covered by the --cache-sksl. I noticed that especially gradients in BoxDecorations are not covered by the --cache-sksl. 
This code in PaintingBinding.shaderWarmUp helps in my case to prevent some cache misses.

```
var linearPaint = Paint()
      ..shader = LinearGradient(
        colors: const [
          Color(0xFFF09819),
          Color(0xFFEDDE5D),
          Color(0xFFDFAF4F),
        ],
        begin: Alignment.topLeft,
        end: Alignment.bottomRight,
      ).createShader(rrect.outerRect);

    canvas.save();
    canvas.drawPaint(linearPaint);
    canvas.translate(drawCallSpacing, 0.0);
    canvas.drawPaint(linearPaint);
    canvas.restore();
```

I don't know if it is necessary to call .translate(). But this was often used in the DefaultShaderWarmUp so I added this.

@zanderso I have now tried to create a reproducible example, but I believe this is a more complex problem.
With a simple example I have not been able to repoduce this.

@dnfield If I start a run with --cache-sksl which is the shader warmup routine, then when I compile with the shader bundle it still gives cache misses again. 
As soon as I re-enable the shader routine and combine this with the shader bundle there are no more misses or it takes much less time to generate this shader.

Here is the profiler with activated warmup routine:
![with-shader-warmup](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18357332/130845257-69890c26-6449-41aa-b563-0d97077fbb83.png)


Here without:
![without-shader-warmup](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18357332/130845568-29d328ce-329c-4a3f-9813-3caee41c9c31.png)


Both times the app was started like this:
flutter run --profile --bundle-sksl-path flutter_01.sksl.json --trace-skia

Important in the shader routine are these calls.
Without this the profiler looks like no shader warmup routine is running.

```
 canvas.save();
  var shapeDecoration = ShapeDecoration(
    shape: ContinuousRectangleBorder(
      borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(18),
      side: BorderSide(
        color: Colors.grey,
        width: 1,
      ),
    ),
    gradient: LinearGradient(
      colors: const [
        Color(0xFFF09819),
        Color(0xFFEDDE5D),
        Color(0xFFDFAF4F),
      ],
      begin: Alignment.topLeft,
      end: Alignment.bottomRight,
    ),
  );
  shapeDecoration
      .createBoxPainter(() {})
      .paint(canvas, Offset(27, 27), ImageConfiguration(size: Size(300, 27)));
  canvas.restore();
```

I use this decoration the exact same way in the app

@b3nni97 which version/channel of flutter do you use in which you can run the command 
`flutter run --profile --bundle-sksl-path flutter_01.sksl.json --trace-skia`?

With flutter 2.2.2 I get `Could not find an option named "bundle-sksl-path".` error

@dnfield In the [documentation](https://docs.flutter.dev/perf/rendering/shader#how-to-use-sksl-warmup) concerning the shader compilation jank the following is stated: 

> The CI system [of Flutter Gallery] is set up to generate SkSLs for every Flutter commit

Could you elaborate how this was done? The profile mode can only be executed on physical devices, therefore it is not clear, how to automate the generation on the SkSLs.

@acoutts: 
> Can we continue to use sksl warmup in the meantime or does it not have any effect for iOS now?

Packaging SKSL has no effect on iOS. You can continue to do so but it will not affect rendering at all.

@m-j-g (in a comment that has since been deleted but I got a GitHub email notification for):
> Worth noting that impeller is currently broken on the latest version of iOS, 16.6...

Assuming you are talking about https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/131319. This does [**not** affect Impeller at ToT or in 3.13](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/131319#issuecomment-1667779030). It affects all versions of the legacy renderer. We are still trying to wrap our heads around how iOS behavior changed so drastically in a point release. But we know what fixes the issue (since Impeller already doesn't exhibit it at ToT) and are trying to figure out how/if we should backport it and investigate the same fix in the legacy renderer. If you are aware of an Impeller specific performance issue however, please file a bug and we'll investigate it immediately.
